            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adam Castillo\u2019s path to San Francisco was paved with the empathy forged in his San Leandro childhood. Raised by his Mexican-American father, a carpenter, and his white mother, a teacher\u2019s aide, Adam grew up understanding the value of hard work and community support. The turning point came in his teens while watching his younger sister navigate severe anxiety. The school's social worker was her lifeline, and for Adam, a career path was illuminated. He saw firsthand how one dedicated professional could stabilize a family.\n\nHe pursued his Bachelor's at SF State, immersing himself in the city's culture while staying close to home. He later earned his Master of Social Work from UC Berkeley, solidifying his commitment to youth mental health. Now a Licensed Clinical Social Worker, he feels he\u2019s come full circle, working within the San Francisco Unified School District. He provides counseling and crisis intervention for students grappling with everything from academic pressure to housing instability\u2014issues he understands intimately.\n\nAdam\u2019s life is rooted in a quiet rhythm. He lives in a small apartment in the Inner Richmond, his daily 3.8-mile commute on the 5-Fulton Muni a time for reflection before facing the emotional turbulence of high school hallways. Fresh out of a long-term relationship last year, his social life currently centers on a close-knit group of friends. They share beers at neighborhood pubs, hike in the Headlands, and decompress from their demanding service-oriented jobs.\n\nWith an income of $98,000, he lives comfortably but consciously, the city's high cost of living a shared stressor with many of the students he counsels. Adam loves San Francisco for its progressive ideals and the easy access to nature, often finding peace on runs through Golden Gate Park. He dreams not of wealth, but of deeper impact\u2014perhaps one day opening his own youth-focused community clinic. For now, he finds fulfillment in the small victories: a student\u2019s breakthrough, a moment of earned trust, and the feeling of giving back to the Bay Area that raised him."
