        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was sixteen, waiting in the car outside the county building. His sister got in, silent as usual, and stared out the window. Then, quietly, she started humming a song from the radio, something she hadn't done in months. Adam looked over and saw the tension had drained from her small shoulders. It was the first glimpse of her old self he'd seen since the anxiety took hold. In that moment, watching his sister's fragile peace, he didn\u2019t just understand the social worker's job; he felt its power as a tangible, life-altering force.\n\n2.\nHis junior year at SF State, he and his roommates skipped class for the first clear day in weeks. They took the N-Judah to Ocean Beach, the air sharp with salt. They had no plan, just cheap sandwiches and a frisbee. As the sun set, turning the sky a fierce, bruised orange behind the Farallones, Adam felt a profound sense of rightness. This city, with its freezing ocean and sudden beauty, was not just a temporary stop for a degree. It was home. That feeling settled deep in his bones, a permanent anchor.\n\n3.\nThe student, a boy named Marcus, hadn't said more than three words in six sessions. Adam was almost ready to change his approach. Then, while doodling on a notepad, Marcus slid a drawing across the desk. It was a minutely detailed sketch of his crowded apartment, with a small figure tucked into a closet. Below it, he\u2019d written: \"The only quiet place.\" A wave of validation washed over Adam, so strong it felt like a current. It cemented his belief that patience was a form of communication, that trust is built in silence, not demands.\n\n4.\nA few months after the breakup, he forced himself to hike the Marin Headlands alone. The trail was steep, his lungs burning. At the top, Karl the Fog was swallowing the Golden Gate Bridge, leaving only the tops of the towers visible. The wind was relentless. He felt utterly solitary, a single point in a vast, indifferent landscape. Yet, instead of loneliness, a quiet strength bloomed in his chest. He realized his peace didn't have to be co-created; it was his own, something he could find for himself, right here.\n\n5.\nRiding the 5-Fulton home, he overheard two kids from his high school talking in the seat behind him. They weren't discussing homework, but how their landlord had illegally raised the rent again. Adam, who had just spent his lunch hour rejiggering his own budget, felt a quiet, gut-level kinship. The line between his own lived reality and the crises he counseled his students through dissolved completely. The city\u2019s pressure was a weight they all carried, and his work felt less like a service and more like a shared act of survival."
